<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-285-839  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 285 839.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Spectrum  Jan 1990 v27 n1 p52(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Biomedical engineering Randamp;D picks up.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Walker, Cedric F.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Biomedical engineering is experiencing advances in theunderstanding of magnetic fields in biological systems,micromachining, the use of computer imaging, and integrateddiagnostic/therapeutic devices for improved care delivery.andP;  Animproved understanding of the effects of magnetic fields on thecentral nervous system combined with advances in room-temperaturesuperconductors may lead to new classes of therapeutic anddiagnostic devices.andP;  The Food and Drug Administration has approveda nitroprusside infusion controller that automatically monitorsblood pressure and delivers the appropriate amount of drug tocontrol it.andP;  Integrated circuit fabrication technology will beused to micromachine microscale mechanical systems for suchapplications as cutters to remove obstructions in diseasedarteries.andP;  Use of imaging systems for surgery is also discussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Medical DiagnosisMedical ResearchBiomedical EngineeringTrendsSystem DevelopmentMagnetic Fields.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>